                "comment_count": 0,
                "committer": {
                    "date": "2026-05-11T04:51:50Z",
                    "email": "bjodah@gmail.com",
                    "name": "Bjorn"
                },
                "message": "Code review (GPT-5.5 High)\n\n1. cython/tests/compile/cpp_vector_to_py_dedup_T6981.pyx:2 is missing no-cpp-locals.\n   As committed, python3 runtests.py -vv --backends=cpp cpp_vector_to_py_dedup_T6981 fails on the patched branch because the test runner automatically reruns C++ tests with cpp_locals=True. That variant fails with __Pyx_Optional_Type<std::vector<double> > assignment/conversion errors, not with the duplicate utility\n   issue. Add:\n\n   # tag: cpp, no-cpp-locals\n   unless the patch is intended to fix the separate cpp_locals failure too.\n\nSoundness\n\nThe actual compiler change looks sound for gh-6981. Switching C++ conversion utility generation from local env.directives to env.global_scope().directives at cython/Cython/Compiler/PyrexTypes.py:4252 and cython/Cython/Compiler/PyrexTypes.py:4301 is defensible: the generated helper has one fixed C name, so allowing\nlocal directive differences to produce distinct CythonUtilityCode objects with the same C function name is unsafe. This also matches nearby patterns for other generated conversion helpers.\n\nResidual caveat: this deliberately stops local-scope directives from influencing these C++ conversion utilities. Given the helper naming does not encode directive state, that is probably the right tradeoff.\n\nVerification\n\nPatched branch:\n\n- Direct MWE Cythonization emits one helper: count=1.\n- python3 runtests.py -vv --backends=cpp --no-cpp-locals cpp_vector_to_py_dedup_T6981: passed.\n- python3 runtests.py -vv --backends=cpp cpp_vector_to_py_dedup_T6981: failed due the cpp_locals variant.\n- Adjacent tests passed with --no-cpp-locals:\n  cpp_stl_conversion cyfunction_defaults_cpp cpp_templates_nested fused_cpp.\n\nWithout patch:\n\n- I created a detached HEAD^ worktree, copied in only the new test, and ran:\n  python3 runtests.py -vv --backends=cpp --no-cpp-locals cpp_vector_to_py_dedup_T6981.\n- It failed as expected with duplicate __pyx_convert_vector_to_py_double.\n\nSo: compiler fix looks good; test needs no-cpp-locals or the branch will fail normal targeted test runs.",
